  <exercisegroup>
    <title>Pour se pratiquer</title>

    <!-- No 1 -->
    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2016D</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li><p>
      Quelques courbes de niveau de la fonction <m>f(x,y)</m> sont esquissées dans le plan <m>xy</m> ci-dessous.
      </p>

      <sidebyside width="75%">
        <image source="images/CLP-figs/pfigs/OE16D_2a"/>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
      Pour chacun des énoncés ci-dessous, encercler la lettre de
      <alert>tous</alert> les points dans le diagramme où la situation s'applique.
      Par exemple, si l'énoncé était <q>Ces points sont sur l'axe <m>y</m></q>, vous encercleriez <m>P</m> et <m>U</m>, mais aucune des autres lettres.
      Vous pouvez prendre pour acquis qu'un maximum local se produit au point <m>T</m>.
      <md>
        <mrow>
        \text{(i) }&amp; \vnabla f\text{ est nul} &amp; &amp;\text{P R S T U}
        </mrow><mrow>
        \text{(ii) }&amp; f \text{ a un point de selle} &amp; &amp;\text{P R S T U}
        </mrow><mrow>
        \text{(iii) }&amp; \text{ la dérivée partielle $f_y$ est positive} &amp; &amp;\text{P R S T U}
        </mrow><mrow>
        \text{(iv) }&amp; \text{ la dérivée directionnelle de $f$ dans la
                         direction $\llt 0,-1\rgt$ is} &amp; &amp;\text{P R S T U}
        </mrow><mrow>
                  &amp; \text{ négative} &amp; &amp;
        </mrow>
      </md>
      </p></li>
      <li><p>
      Le diagramme ci-dessous montre trois <q>traces <m>y</m></q> d'un graphe <m>z=F(x,y)</m> esquissé
      sur les axes <m>xz</m>. (Autrement dit, les intersections de la surface  <m>z=F(x,y)</m> avec les trois plans (<m>y=1.9</m>, <m>y=2</m>, <m>y=2.1</m>). Pour chaque énoncé ci-dessous, encercler le bon mot.
      <md>
        <mrow>
        \text{(i) }&amp; \text{ la dérivée partielle de premier ordre}\ F_x(1,2)\ \text{est} &amp; &amp;
        \text{positive/négative/nulle}
        </mrow><mrow>
        \text{(ii) }&amp; F \text{ a un point critique en } (2,2) &amp;
                 &amp;\text{vrai/faux}
        </mrow><mrow>
        \text{(iii) }&amp; \text{ la dérivée partielle de deuxième ordre}\ F_x(1,2)\ \text{est} &amp; &amp;\text{positive/négative/nulle}
        </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>
      <sidebyside width="66%">
        <image source="images/CLP-figs/pfigs/OE16D_2b"/>
      </sidebyside>
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
        (a) (i) <m>T</m>, <m>U</m>
        </p>

        <p>(a) (ii) <m>U</m>
        </p>

        <p>(a) (iii) <m>S</m>
        </p>

        <p>(a) (iv) <m>S</m>
        </p>

        <p>(b) (i) <m>F_x(1,2) \gt 0</m>
        </p>

        <p>(b) (ii) <m>F</m> n'a <em>pas</em> de point critique en <m>(2,2)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>(b) (iii) <m>F_{xy}(1,2) \lt 0</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      a) (i) <m>\vnabla f</m> is zero at critical points.
              The point <m>T</m> is a local maximum and the point <m>U</m> is
              a saddle point. The remaining points <m>P</m>, <m>R</m>, <m>S</m>, are not
              critical points.
      </p>

      <p>(a) (ii) Only <m>U</m> is a saddle point.
      </p>

      <p>(a) (iii) We have <m>f_y(x,y) \gt 0</m> if <m>f</m> increases as you move vertically upward
                through <m>(x,y)</m>. Looking at the diagram, we see
      <md>
      <mrow>
      f_y(P)  &amp;\lt 0&amp;
      f_y(Q)  &amp;\lt 0&amp;
      f_y(R) &amp;=0</mrow><mrow>
      f_y(S)  &amp;\gt 0&amp;
      f_y(T) &amp;=0&amp;
      f_y(U) &amp;=0
      </mrow>
      </md>
      So only <m>S</m> works.
      </p>

      <p>(a) (iv) The directional derivative of <m>f</m> in the direction <m>\llt 0,-1\rgt</m>
                 is <m>\vnabla f\cdot \llt 0,-1\rgt =-f_y</m>. It is negative if and
                 only if <m>f_y \gt 0</m>. So, again, only <m>S</m> works.
      </p>

      <p>(b) (i) The function <m>z=F(x,2)</m> is increasing at <m>x=1</m>,
           because the <m>y=2.0</m> graph in the diagram has positive slope at <m>x=1</m>.
           So <m>F_x(1,2) \gt 0</m>.
      </p>

      <p>(b) (ii) The function <m>z=F(x,2)</m> is also increasing (though slowly) at <m>x=2</m>,
           because the <m>y=2.0</m> graph in the diagram has positive slope at <m>x=2</m>.
           So <m>F_x(2,2) \gt 0</m>. So <m>F</m> does <em>not</em> have a critical point
           at <m>(2,2)</m>.
      </p>

      <p>(b) (iii) From the diagram the looks like
                      <m>F_x(1,1.9)  \gt  F_x(1,2.0)  \gt  F_x(1,2.1)</m>.
            That is, it looks like the slope of the <m>y=1.9</m> graph at <m>x=1</m>
                   is larger than the slope of the <m>y=2.0</m> graph at <m>x=1</m>,
                   which in turn
                   is larger than the slope of the <m>y=2.1</m> graph at <m>x=1</m>.
           So it looks like <m>F_x(1,y)</m> decreases as <m>y</m> increases through <m>y=2</m>,
           and consequently <m>F_{xy}(1,2) \lt 0</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>
    <!-- No 3 -->
    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2005D</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Soit <m>z = f(x,y) = {(y^2 - x^2)}^2</m>.
      <ol marker = "(a)">
      <li>
      Faire une esquisse raisonnablement précise des courbes de niveau dans le plan <m>xy</m> de <m>z = f(x,y)</m> pour <m>z = 0</m>, <m>1</m> et <m>16</m>. Assurez-vous de montrer les unités sur les axes de coordonnées.
      </li>
      <li>
      Vérifiez que <m>(0,0)</m> est un point critique pour <m>z = f(x,y)</m>, et
      déterminez de la partie (a) ou directement de la formule pour <m>f(x,y)</m>
      si <m>(0, 0)</m> est un minimum local, un maximum local ou un point de selle.
      </li>
      <li>
      Pouvez-vous utiliser le test de la dérivée seconde afin de déterminer si le point critique
      <m>(0, 0)</m> est un minimum local, un maximum local ou
      un point de selle? Donnez des raisons pour votre réponse.
      </li>
      </ol>
      </p>

      </statement>

      <hint><p>
      Écrivez les équations des courbes de niveau spécifiées.
      </p></hint>

      <answer>
      <sidebyside widths="10% 60%">
      <p>(a)</p>
      <image source="images/CLP-figs/pfigs/OE05D_5"/>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
      (b) <m>(0,0)</m> est un minimum local (et aussi absolu).
      </p>

      <p>(c)
      Notez que
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      f_{xx}(x,y) &amp;=-4y^2+12x^2\qquad&amp;
               f_{xx}(x,y)&amp;=0
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{yy}(x,y) &amp;= 12y^2-4x^2\qquad&amp;
               f_{yy}(x,y)&amp;=0
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{xy}(x,y) &amp;=-8xy\qquad&amp;
               f_{xx}(x,y)&amp;=0
      </mrow>
      </md>
      Comme
      <m>
      f_{xx}(0,0)f_{yy}(0,0)-f_{xy}(0,0)^2=0
      </m>,
      le test de la dérivée seconde (<xref ref="thm_second_deriv_test"/>) ne dit rien.
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      (a)
      <ul>
      <li>
      The level curve <m>z=0</m> is <m>y^2-x^2=0</m>, which is the pair
      of <m>45^\circ</m> lines <m>y=\pm x</m>.
      </li>
      <li>
      When <m>C \gt 0</m>, the level curve
      <m>z=C^4</m> is <m>{(y^2-x^2)}^2=C^4</m>, which is the pair of hyperbolae
      <m>y^2-x^2=C^2</m>, <m>y^2-x^2=-C^2</m> or
      <me>
      y=\pm\sqrt{x^2+C^2}\qquad x=\pm\sqrt{y^2+C^2}
      </me>
      The hyperbola  <m>y^2-x^2=C^2</m> crosses the <m>y</m>--axis (i.e. the line <m>x=0</m>)
      at <m>(0,\pm C)</m>.
      The hyperbola  <m>y^2-x^2=-C^2</m> crosses the <m>x</m>--axis (i.e. the line <m>y=0</m>)
      at <m>(\pm C,0)</m>.
      </li>
      </ul>
      Here is a sketch showing the level curves <m>z=0</m>, <m>z=1</m> (i.e. <m>C=1</m>),
      and <m>z=16</m> (i.e. <m>C=2</m>).
      </p>
      <sidebyside width="60%">
        <image source="images/CLP-figs/pfigs/OE05D_5"/>
      </sidebyside>

      <p>
      (b)
      As <m>f_x(x,y)=-4x(y^2-x^2)</m> and <m>f_y(x,y)=4y(y^2-x^2)</m>, we have
      <m>f_x(0,0) = f_y(0,0) = 0</m> so that <m>(0,0)</m> is a critical point. Note that
      <ul>
      <li>
      <m>f(0,0)=0</m>,
      </li>
      <li>
      <m>f(x,y)\geqslant 0</m> for all <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
      </li>
      </ul>
      So <m>(0,0)</m> is a local (and also absolute) minimum.
      </p>

      <p>(c)
      Notez que
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      f_{xx}(x,y) &amp;=-4y^2+12x^2\qquad&amp;
               f_{xx}(x,y)&amp;=0
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{yy}(x,y) &amp;= 12y^2-4x^2\qquad&amp;
               f_{yy}(x,y)&amp;=0
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{xy}(x,y) &amp;=-8xy\qquad&amp;
               f_{xx}(x,y)&amp;=0
      </mrow>
      </md>
      Comme
      <m>
      f_{xx}(0,0)f_{yy}(0,0)-f_{xy}(0,0)^2=0
      </m>,
      le test de la dérivée seconde (<xref ref="thm_second_deriv_test"/>) ne dit rien.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <!-- No 5 -->
    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2006A</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Utilisez le test de la dérivée seconde pour trouver toutes les valeurs de la constante <m>c</m>
      pour lesquelles la fonction <m>z = x^2 + cxy + y^2</m> admet un point de selle en <m>(0,0)</m>.
      </p></statement>

      <answer><p>
      <m>|c| \gt 2</m>
      </p></answer>

      <solution><p>
      Write <m>f(x,y) = x^2 +cxy +y^2</m>. Then
      <md>
      <mrow>
      f_x(x,y)&amp;= 2x+cy &amp; f_x(0,0) = 0
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_y(x,y)&amp;= cx+2y &amp; f_y(0,0) = 0
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{xx}(x,y) &amp;= 2
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{xy}(x,y) &amp;= c
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_{yy}(x,y) &amp;= 2
      </mrow>
      </md>
      As <m>f_x(0,0)=f_y(0,0)=0</m>, we have that <m>(0,0)</m> is always a critical point
      for <m>f</m>. According to the Second Derivative Test, <m>(0,0)</m> is also a saddle point
      for <m>f</m> if
      <md>
      <mrow>
      f_{xx}(0,0) f_{yy}(0,0) - f_{xy}(0,0)^2  \lt 0
      \iff 4-c^2  \lt 0
      \iff |c| \gt 2
      </mrow>
      </md>
      </p>

      <p>As a remark, the Second Derivative Test provides no information
      when the expression
      <m>f_{xx}(0,0) f_{yy}(0,0) - f_{xy}(0,0)^2 =0</m>, i.e. when <m>c=\pm 2</m>.
      But when <m>c=\pm 2</m>,
      <me>
      f(x,y) =  x^2 \pm 2xy + y^2 =(x\pm y)^2
      </me>
      and <m>f</m> has a local minimum, not a saddle point, at <m>(0,0)</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>

    <!-- No 6 -->
    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2006D</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement>
      <p>
      Trouvez et classifiez tous les points critiques de la fonction
      <me>
      f(x, y) = x^3 - y^3 - 2xy + 6.
      </me>
      </p>
      </statement>

      <answer>

      <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
      <col halign="center"/> <col />
      <row>
      <cell>   <m>\Atop{\text{point}}{\text{critique}}</m> </cell><cell> type </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>
               <m>(0,0)</m> </cell><cell> point de selle  </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>      <m>\left(-\frac{2}{3},\frac{2}{3}\right)</m> </cell><cell> maximum local </cell>
      </row>
      </tabular></sidebyside>

      </answer>

      <solution><p>
      To find the critical points we will need the gradient of <m>f</m>, and to
      apply the second derivative test of
      Theorem <xref ref="thm_second_deriv_test"/>
      we will need all second order partial derivatives. So we need all
      partial derivatives of <m>f</m> up to order two.
      Here they are.
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      f&amp;=x^3 - y^3 - 2xy + 6
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_x&amp;=3x^2-2y   &amp; f_{xx}&amp;=6x \qquad &amp; f_{xy}&amp;= -2
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_y&amp;=-3y^2-2x \qquad &amp; f_{yy}&amp;=-6y\qquad &amp; f_{yx}&amp;= -2
      </mrow>
      </md>
      The critical points are the solutions of
      <me>
      f_x=3x^2-2y=0   \qquad
      f_y=-3y^2-2x = 0
      </me>
      Substituting <m>y=\frac{3}{2}x^2</m>, from the first equation, into the
      second equation gives
      <md>
      <mrow>
      -3\left(\frac{3}{2}x^2\right)^2-2x =0
      &amp;\iff -2x\left(\frac{3^3}{2^3}x^3+1\right)=0
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\iff x=0,\ -\frac{2}{3}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      So there are two critical points: <m>(0,0)</m>,
              <m>\left(-\frac{2}{3},\frac{2}{3}\right)</m>.
      </p>

      <p>The classification is</p>

      <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
      <col />  <col halign="center"/>  <col halign="center"/> <col />
      <row>
      <cell>   <m>\Atop{\text{critical}}{\text{point}}</m>  </cell><cell> <m>f_{xx}f_{yy}-f_{xy}^2</m> </cell><cell>
                                                                <m>f_{xx}</m> </cell><cell> type </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>
               <m>(0,0)</m>  </cell><cell> <m>0\times 0 -(-2)^2  \lt  0</m> </cell><cell>   </cell><cell> saddle point  </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>      <m>\left(-\frac{2}{3},\frac{2}{3}\right)</m>  </cell><cell> <m>(-4)\times (-4)-(-2)^2 \gt 0</m> </cell><cell>
                            <m>-4</m> </cell><cell> local max </cell>
      </row>
      </tabular></sidebyside>

      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <!-- No 7 -->
    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2007A</fromexam></title> -->
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez tous les points critiques pour <m>f(x,y) = x(x^2 + xy + y^2 - 9)</m>.
      Également, trouvez les points parmi ces points qui donnent des maximums locaux pour
      <m>f(x,y)</m>, qui donnent des minimum locaux, et qui donnent des points de selles.
      </p></statement>

      <answer>

      <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
      <col halign="center"/> <col />
      <row>
      <cell>   <m>\Atop{\text{Point}}{\text{critique}}</m>   </cell><cell> type </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>
               <m>(0,3)</m>  </cell><cell>   point de selle  </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>      <m>(0,-3)</m>  </cell><cell>  point de selle </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>       <m>(-2,1)</m>  </cell><cell>  maximum local </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>       <m>(2,-1)</m>  </cell><cell>  minimum local </cell>
      </row>
      </tabular></sidebyside>

      </answer>

      <solution><p>
      To find the critical points we will need the
      gradient of <m>f</m>, and to apply the second derivative test of
      Theorem <xref ref="thm_second_deriv_test"/>
      we will need all
      second order partial derivatives. So we need all partial derivatives of
      <m>f</m> up to order two.
      Here they are.
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      f&amp;=x^3 + x^2y + xy^2 - 9x
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_x&amp;=3x^2+2xy+y^2-9 \qquad   &amp; f_{xx}&amp;=6x+2y \qquad &amp; f_{xy}&amp;= 2x+2y
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_y&amp;=x^2+2xy  &amp; f_{yy}&amp;=2x\qquad &amp; f_{yx}&amp;= 2x+2y
      </mrow>
      </md>
      (Of course, <m>f_{xy}</m> and <m>f_{yx}</m> have to be the same. It is still
      useful to compute both, as a way to catch some mechanical errors.)
      </p>

      <p>The critical points are the solutions of
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      f_x&amp;=3x^2+2xy+y^2-9&amp;&amp;=0  \tag{E1}
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_y&amp;=x(x+2y) &amp;&amp;= 0  \tag{E2}
      </mrow>
      </md>
      Equation (E2) is satisfied if at least one of <m>x=0</m>, <m>x=-2y</m>.
      <ul>
      <li> If <m>x=0</m>, equation (E1) reduces to <m>y^2-9=0</m>,
      which is satisfied if <m>y=\pm 3</m>.
      </li>
      <li> If <m>x=-2y</m>, equation (E1) reduces to
      <md>
      <mrow>
      0=3(-2y)^2+2(-2y)y+y^2-9=9y^2-9
      </mrow>
      </md>
      which is satisfied if <m>y=\pm 1</m>.
      </li>
      </ul>
      </p>

      <p>So there are four critical points: <m>(0,3)</m>, <m>(0,-3)</m>, <m>(-2,1)</m> and <m>(2,-1)</m>.
      The classification is</p>

      <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
      <col />  <col halign="center"/>  <col halign="center"/> <col />
      <row>
      <cell>   <m>\Atop{\text{critical}}{\text{point}}</m>  </cell><cell> <m>f_{xx}f_{yy}-f_{xy}^2</m> </cell><cell>
                                                                <m>f_{xx}</m> </cell><cell> type </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>
               <m>(0,3)</m>  </cell><cell>
                 <m>(6)\times (0)-(6)^2 \lt  0</m> </cell><cell>   </cell><cell>
                                                      saddle point  </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>      <m>(0,-3)</m>  </cell><cell>
             <m>(-6)\times (0)-(-6)^2 \lt 0</m> </cell><cell>  </cell><cell>
                                                      saddle point </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>       <m>(-2,1)</m>  </cell><cell>
             <m>(-10)\times (-4)-(-2)^2 \gt 0</m> </cell><cell>  <m>-10</m> </cell><cell>
                                                      local max </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>       <m>(2,-1)</m>  </cell><cell>
             <m>(10)\times (4)-(2)^2 \gt 0</m>   </cell><cell> <m>10</m> </cell><cell>
                                                      local min </cell>
      </row>
      </tabular></sidebyside>

      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <!-- No 9 -->
    <exercise>
      <statement><p>
      Trouvez et classifiez tous les points critiques de <m>f(x,y)=x^2+y^2+x^2y+4</m>.
      </p></statement>

      <answer>

      <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
      <col halign="center"/> <col />
      <row>
      <cell>   <m>\Atop{\text{Point}}{\text{critique}}</m>  </cell><cell> type </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>       <m>(0,0)</m>           </cell><cell>    Minimum local  </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>      <m>(\sqrt{2},-1)</m>   </cell><cell> point de selle  </cell>
      </row><row>
      <cell>      <m>(-\sqrt{2},-1)</m>  </cell><cell> point de selle  </cell>
      </row>
      </tabular></sidebyside>

      </answer>

      <solution><p>
      To find the critical points we will need the
      gradient of <m>f</m>, and to apply the second derivative test of
      Theorem <xref ref="thm_second_deriv_test"/>
      we will need all second order partial derivatives. So we need
      all partial derivatives of <m>f</m> up to order two. Here they are.
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      f&amp;=x^2+y^2+x^2y+4
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_x&amp;=2x+2xy\qquad &amp; f_{xx}&amp;=2+2y\qquad &amp; f_{xy}&amp;= 2x
      </mrow><mrow>
      f_y&amp;=2y+x^2 &amp; f_{yy}&amp;=2
      </mrow>
      </md>
      The critical points are the solutions of
      <md alignment="alignat">
      <mrow>
      &amp; &amp; &amp;f_x=0  &amp; &amp;f_y=0
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\iff\quad &amp; &amp;2x(1+y)=0  &amp; &amp;2y+x^2=0
      </mrow><mrow>
      &amp;\iff &amp; &amp;x=0\text{ or }y=-1\qquad &amp; &amp;2y+x^2=0
      </mrow>
      </md>
      When <m>x=0</m>, <m>y</m> must be <m>0</m>. When <m>y=-1</m>, <m>x^2</m> must be <m>2</m>.
      So, there are three critical points: <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>\big(\pm\sqrt{2},-1\big)</m>.
