    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2002A</fromexam></title> -->
        <statement><p>
        Une plaque en métal est en forme de demi-disque borné par l'axe <m>x</m> et la moitié supérieure de <m>x^2+y^2=4</m>. La température au
        point <m>(x,y)</m> est donnée par <m>T(x,y)=\ln\big(1+x^2+y^2\big)-y</m>. Trouvez le point le plus froid sur la plaque, en expliquant vos étapes soigneusement. (Note:
        <m>\ln 2\approx 0.693</m>, <m>\ln 5\approx 1.609</m>)
        </p></statement>

        <answer><p>
        La température la plus froide est <m>-0.391</m> et le point le plus froid est <m>(0,2)</m>.
        </p></answer>

        <solution><p>
        The coldest point must be either on the boundary of the plate
        or in the interior of the plate.
        <ul>
        <li>
        On the semi--circular part of the boundary <m>0\leqslant y\leqslant 2</m> and
        <m>x^2+y^2=4</m> so that <m>T=\ln\big(1+x^2+y^2\big)-y=\ln 5-y</m>. The smallest
        value of <m>\ln 5-y</m> is taken when <m>y</m> is as large as possible,
        i.e. when <m>y=2</m>, and is <m>\ln 5 -2\approx -0.391</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
        On the flat part of the boundary, <m>y=0</m> and
        <m>-2\leqslant x\leqslant 2</m> so that <m>T=\ln\big(1+x^2+y^2\big)-y=\ln\big(1+x^2\big)</m>.
        The smallest value of <m>\ln\big(1+x^2\big)</m> is taken when <m>x</m> is as small as possible, i.e. when <m>x=0</m>, and is <m>0</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
        If the coldest point is in the interior of the plate,
        it must be at a critical point of <m>T(x,y)</m>. Since
        <md>
        <mrow>
        T_x(x,y)=\frac{2x}{1+x^2+y^2}\qquad
        T_y(x,y)=\frac{2y}{1+x^2+y^2}-1
        </mrow>
        </md>
        a critical point must have <m>x=0</m> and <m>\frac{2y}{1+x^2+y^2}-1=0</m>,
        which is the case if and only if <m>x=0</m> and <m>2y-1-y^2=0</m>. So the only
        critical point is <m>x=0,\ y=1</m>, where <m>T=\ln 2-1\approx -0.307</m>.
        </li>
        </ul>
        Since <m>-0.391 \lt -0.307 \lt 0</m>, the coldest temperture is <m>-0.391</m> and the
        coldest point is <m>(0,2)</m>.
        </p></solution>
      </exercise>

    <!-- No 32 -->
    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2009D</fromexam></title> -->
        <statement><p>
        La température <m>T(x,y)</m> à un point du plan <m>xy</m> est donnée par
        <me>
        T(x,y) = 20 - 4x^2 - y^2
        </me>
        <ol marker = "(a)">
        <li>
        Trouvez la valeur maximale et minimale de <m>T(x,y)</m> sur le disque <m>D</m>
        défini par <m>x^2 + y^2\leqslant4</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
        Supposons qu'une fourmi vit sur le disque <m>D</m>. Si la fourmi est initiallement au point
        <m>(1, 1)</m>, dans quelle direction doit-elle se déplacer afin que la température croît le plus vite possible?
        </li>
        <li>
        Supposons que la fourmi se déplace à une vitesse <m>\vv = -2\vi - \vj</m>.
        Quel est le taux de variation de la température lorsqu'elle passe par <m>(1, 1)</m>?
        </li>
        <li>
        Supposons que la fourmi est contrainte à rester sur la courbe <m>y = 2 - x^2</m>.
        Où devrait-elle aller si elle veut être le plus au chaud possible?
        </li>
        </ol>
        </p></statement>

        <answer><p>
        (a) La valeur maximale et minimale de <m>T(x,y)</m> dans <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 4</m>
             sont <m>20</m> (à <m>(0,0)</m>) et  <m>4</m> (à <m>(\pm 2,0)</m>), respectivement.
        </p>

        <p>(b) <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{17}}\llt -4,-1\rgt</m>
        </p><p>
        (c) <m>18</m></p><p>
        (d) <m>(0,2)</m>
        </p></answer>

        <solution><p>
        (a)
        The maximum and minimum can occur either in the interior
            of the disk or on the boundary of the disk. The boundary
            of the disk is the circle <m>x^2+y^2=4</m>.
        <ul>
        <li> Any absolute max or min in the interior of the disk
              must also be a local max or min and, since there are no
              singular points, must also be a critical point of <m>h</m>.
              Since <m>T_x=-8x</m> and <m>T_y=-2y</m>, the only critical point is
              <m>(x,y)=(0,0)</m>, where <m>T=20</m>.  Since <m>4x^2+y^2\geqslant 0</m>,
              we have <m>T(x,y)=20-4x^2-y^2\leqslant 20</m>. So the maximum value
              of <m>T</m> (even in <m>\R^2</m>) is <m>20</m>.
        </li>
        <li> At each point of <m>x^2+y^2=4</m> we have
                   <m>T(x,y)=20-4x^2-y^2=20 -4x^2-(4-x^2)=16-3x^2</m>
                   with <m>-2\leqslant x\leqslant 2</m>. So <m>T</m> is a minimum when <m>x^2</m> is a maximum.
                   Thus the minimum value of <m>T</m> on the disk is <m>16-3(\pm 2)^2=4</m>.
        </li>
        </ul>
        So all together, the maximum and minimum values of <m>T(x,y)</m> in <m>x^2+y^2\leqslant 4</m>
             are <m>20</m> (at <m>(0,0)</m>) and  <m>4</m> (at <m>(\pm 2,0)</m>), respectively.
        </p>

        <p>(b) To increase its temperature as quickly as possible, the ant should
            move in the direction of the temperature gradient
            <m>\vnabla T(1,1)=\llt -8x,-2y\rgt\Big|_{(x,y)=(1,1)}=\llt -8,-2\rgt</m>.
            A unit vector in that direction is <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{17}}\llt -4,-1\rgt</m>.
        </p>

        <p>(c) The ant's rate f increase of temperature (per unit time) is
        <md>
        <mrow>
         \vnabla T(1,1)\cdot\llt -2,-1\rgt
        =\llt -8,-2\rgt\cdot\llt -2,-1\rgt
        =18
        </mrow>
        </md>
        </p>

        <p>(d) We are being asked to find the <m>(x,y)=(x,2-x^2)</m> which maximizes
        <md>
        <mrow>
        T\big(x,2-x^2\big) =20 -4x^2-\big(2-x^2\big)^2
                           = 16-x^4
        </mrow>
        </md>
        The maximum of <m>16-x^4</m> is obviously <m>16</m> at <m>x=0</m>. So the ant should
        go to <m>\big(0,2-0^2\big)=(0,2)</m>.
        </p></solution>
      </exercise>

    <!-- No 33 -->
    <exercise> <!-- <title><fromexam>M200 2014A</fromexam></title> -->
        <statement><p>
        Considérez la fonction
        <me>
        f (x,y) = 3kx^2 y + y^3 - 3x^2 - 3y^2 + 4
        </me>
        où <m>k  \gt  0</m> est une constante.
        Trouvez et classifiez tous les points critiques de <m>f(x,y)</m> comme étant un minimum local,
        un maximum local, un point de selle ou un point de type indéterminé.
        Distinguer prudemment les cas <m>k  \lt  \frac{1}{2}</m>, <m>k = \frac{1}{2}</m>
        et <m>k  \gt  \frac{1}{2}</m>.
        </p></statement>

        <answer><p>
        <em>Cas <m>k \lt \frac{1}{2}</m>:</em>
        </p>
        <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
        <row>
        <cell>   <m>\Atop{\text{Point}}{\text{critique}}</m>  </cell><cell> type </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>
                 <m>(0,0)</m>   </cell><cell> maximum local  </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>      <m>(0,2)</m>   </cell><cell> point de selle </cell>
        </row>
        </tabular></sidebyside>
        <p>
        <em>Cas <m>k=\frac{1}{2}</m>:</em>
        </p>
        <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
        <row>
        <cell>   <m>\Atop{\text{Point}}{\text{critique}}</m>  </cell><cell> type </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>
                 <m>(0,0)</m>   </cell><cell> maximum local  </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>      <m>(0,2)</m>   </cell><cell> indéterminé </cell>
        </row>
        </tabular></sidebyside>

        <p>
        <em>Cas <m>k \gt \frac{1}{2}</m>:</em>
        </p>
        <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
        <col halign="center"/>  <col />
        <row>
        <cell>   <m>\Atop{\text{Point}}{\text{critique}}</m>   </cell><cell> type </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>
                 <m>(0,0)</m>    </cell><cell> maximum local  </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>      <m>(0,2)</m>    </cell><cell> minimum local </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>       <m>\left(\sqrt{\frac{1}{k^3}(2k-1)}\,,\,\frac{1}{k}\right)</m>
        </cell><cell> point de selle </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>       <m>\left(-\sqrt{\frac{1}{k^3}(2k-1)}\,,\,\frac{1}{k}\right)</m>
        </cell><cell> point de selle </cell>
        </row>
        </tabular></sidebyside>

        </answer>

        <solution><p>
        To find the critical points we will need the
        gradient of <m>f</m> and to apply the second derivative test of
        Theorem <xref ref="thm_second_deriv_test"/>
        we will need all
        second order partial derivatives. So we need all partial derivatives of
        <m>f</m> up to order two.
        Here they are.
        <md alignment="alignat">
        <mrow>
        f&amp;=3kx^2 y + y^3 - 3x^2 - 3y^2 + 4
        </mrow><mrow>
        f_x&amp;=6kxy-6x   &amp; f_{xx}&amp;=6ky-6 \qquad &amp; f_{xy}&amp;= 6kx
        </mrow><mrow>
        f_y&amp;=3kx^2+3y^2-6y \qquad &amp; f_{yy}&amp;=6y-6\qquad &amp; f_{yx}&amp;= 6kx
        </mrow>
        </md>
        (Of course, <m>f_{xy}</m> and <m>f_{yx}</m> have to be the same. It is still
        useful to compute both, as a way to catch some mechanical errors.)
        </p>

        <p>The critical points are the solutions of
        <me>
        f_x=6x(ky-1)=0   \qquad
        f_y=3kx^2+3y^2-6y = 0
        </me>
        The first equation is satisfied if at least one of <m>x=0</m>, <m>y=\frac{1}{k}</m>
        are satisfied. (Recall that <m>k \gt 0</m>.)
        <ul>
        <li>
        If <m>x=0</m>, the second equation reduces to <m>3y(y-2)=0</m>, which is
        satisfied if either <m>y=0</m> or <m>y=2</m>.
        </li>
        <li>
        If <m>y=\frac{1}{k}</m>, the second equation reduces to
        <m>3kx^2+\frac{3}{k^2}-\frac{6}{k}=3kx^2+\frac{3}{k^2}(1-2k)=0</m>.
        </li>
        </ul>
        </p>

        <p><em>Case <m>k \lt \frac{1}{2}</m>:</em>
        If <m>k \lt \frac{1}{2}</m>, then <m>\frac{3}{k^2}(1-2k) \gt 0</m> and the equation
        <m>3kx^2+\frac{3}{k^2}(1-2k)=0</m> has no real solutions. In this case
        there are two critical points: <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>(0,2)</m> and the classification is
        </p>
        <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
        <col halign="center"/>  <col halign="center"/> <col halign="center"/>  <col />
        <row>
        <cell>   <m>\Atop{\text{critical}}{\text{point}}</m>  </cell><cell> <m>f_{xx}f_{yy}-f_{xy}^2</m> </cell><cell>
                                                                  <m>f_{xx}</m> </cell><cell> type </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>
                 <m>(0,0)</m>  </cell><cell> <m>(-6)\times(-6)-(0)^2 \gt  0</m> </cell><cell> <m>-6</m>   </cell><cell> local max  </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>      <m>(0,2)</m>  </cell><cell> <m>(12k-6)\times 6-(0)^2 \lt 0</m> </cell><cell>   </cell><cell> saddle point </cell>
        </row>
        </tabular></sidebyside>

        <p>
        <em>Case <m>k=\frac{1}{2}</m>:</em>
        If <m>k=\frac{1}{2}</m>, then <m>\frac{3}{k^2}(1-2k)=0</m> and the equation
        <m>3kx^2+\frac{3}{k^2}(1-2k)=0</m> reduces to <m>3kx^2=0</m> which has as its only solution <m>x=0</m>. We have already seen this third critical point, <m>x=0</m>, <m>y=\frac{1}{k}=2</m>.
        So there are again two critical points: <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>(0,2)</m> and
        the classification is
        </p>

        <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
        <col halign="center"/>  <col halign="center"/> <col halign="center"/>  <col />
        <row>
        <cell>   <m>\Atop{\text{critical}}{\text{point}}</m>  </cell><cell> <m>f_{xx}f_{yy}-f_{xy}^2</m> </cell><cell>
                                                                  <m>f_{xx}</m> </cell><cell> type </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>
                 <m>(0,0)</m>  </cell><cell> <m>(-6)\times(-6)-(0)^2 \gt  0</m> </cell><cell> <m>-6</m>   </cell><cell> local max  </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>      <m>(0,2)</m>  </cell><cell> <m>(12k-6)\times 6-(0)^2=0</m> </cell><cell>   </cell><cell> unknown </cell>
        </row>
        </tabular></sidebyside>

        <p>
        <em>Case <m>k \gt \frac{1}{2}</m>:</em>
        If <m>k \gt \frac{1}{2}</m>, then <m>\frac{3}{k^2}(1-2k) \lt 0</m> and the equation
        <m>3kx^2+\frac{3}{k^2}(1-2k)=0</m> reduces to <m>3kx^2=\frac{3}{k^2}(2k-1)</m>
        which has two solutions, namely <m>x=\pm\sqrt{\frac{1}{k^3}(2k-1)}</m>.
        So there are four critical points: <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>(0,2)</m>,
        <m>\left(\sqrt{\frac{1}{k^3}(2k-1)}\,,\,\frac{1}{k}\right)</m> and
        <m>\left(-\sqrt{\frac{1}{k^3}(2k-1)}\,,\,\frac{1}{k}\right)</m> and
        the classification is
        </p>

        <sidebyside><tabular left="minor" right="minor" bottom="minor" top="minor">
        <col halign="center"/>  <col halign="center"/> <col halign="center"/>  <col />
        <row>
        <cell>   <m>\Atop{\text{critical}}{\text{point}}</m>  </cell><cell> <m>f_{xx}f_{yy}-f_{xy}^2</m> </cell><cell>
                                                                  <m>f_{xx}</m> </cell><cell> type </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>
                 <m>(0,0)</m>  </cell><cell> <m>(-6)\times(-6)-(0)^2 \gt  0</m> </cell><cell> <m>-6</m>   </cell><cell> local max  </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>      <m>(0,2)</m>  </cell><cell> <m>(12k-6)\times 6-(0)^2 \gt 0</m> </cell><cell> <m>12k-6 \gt 0</m> </cell><cell> local min </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>       <m>\left(\sqrt{\frac{1}{k^3}(2k-1)}\,,\,\frac{1}{k}\right)</m>
                       </cell><cell> <m>(6-6)\times (\frac{6}{k}-6)-( \gt  0)^2 \lt 0</m> </cell><cell>   </cell><cell> saddle point </cell>
        </row><row>
        <cell>       <m>\left(-\sqrt{\frac{1}{k^3}(2k-1)}\,,\,\frac{1}{k}\right)</m>
                       </cell><cell> <m>(6-6)\times (\frac{6}{k}-6)-( \lt  0)^2 \lt 0</m> </cell><cell>   </cell><cell> saddle point </cell>
        </row>
        </tabular></sidebyside>

        </solution>
